Task: Provide an interactive VS Code Desktop inside this Ubuntu sandbox using Xvfb + x11vnc + noVNC, accessible via the platform-provided HTTPS hosts (mapped to ports 12000/12001).

Objective
- Run the VS Code Desktop (Electron) build in a virtual X display and expose it to the browser so we can see and interact with the editor UI, install/run the extension, and capture screenshots or video.

Key constraints and rationale
- Must use VS Code Desktop (Electron). VS Code Web (code-server/openvscode-server) runs only web extensions; our extension relies on Node/Electron modules (e.g., ws) and will not work in the web environment.

Deliverables (Definition of Done)
- A noVNC URL on one of the provided hosts that renders a desktop session with VS Code running.
- We can interact with the UI (mouse/keyboard) and open the Extensions tab.
- We can capture at least one screenshot of the VS Code window via either the noVNC toolbar or command-line capture on the X display.

High-level approach
- Xvfb creates a headless X display (e.g., :1).
- x11vnc exposes that X display over VNC on localhost:5901.
- noVNC + websockify serves a browser-based VNC client on local port 12000 (and optionally 12001). The platform maps these ports to provided HTTPS hosts.
- Launch VS Code Desktop on the X display and access it via the browser.

Security considerations
- Set a VNC password to prevent unauthorized access.
- Keep any secrets out of logs and code; do not commit secrets to version control.
- Use the platform-provided HTTPS hosts. Do NOT append :12000 or :12001 to the browser URL; the host already maps to the allowed port.

Implementation steps

1) Install required packages
- Update apt and install the following:
  apt-get update
  apt-get install -y xvfb x11vnc novnc websockify fluxbox imagemagick wget ca-certificates net-tools

- Install VS Code Desktop (stable .deb). This avoids adding a new apt repo and keeps the setup simple:
  wget -O /tmp/code.deb "https://code.visualstudio.com/sha/download?build=stable&os=linux-deb-x64"
  apt-get install -y /tmp/code.deb

  Notes:
  - Alternatively, VSCodium can be used. The primary requirement is an Electron desktop build, not the web variant.
  - Optional: ffmpeg for screen recording (see below).

2) Create a VNC password
- Create a VNC password file in the current user home. Choose a strong password (or generate one):
  mkdir -p ~/.vnc
  x11vnc -storepasswd "$(openssl rand -base64 24)" ~/.vnc/passwd

  You can also specify your own password instead of a generated one.

3) Start the desktop session and VS Code
- Choose a display and resolution (example: :1 at 1280x800x24). Run the following in a shell:

  export DISPLAY=:1
  Xvfb :1 -screen 0 1280x800x24 -nolisten tcp > /tmp/xvfb.log 2>&1 & echo $! > /tmp/xvfb.pid
  fluxbox -display :1 > /tmp/fluxbox.log 2>&1 & echo $! > /tmp/wm.pid

  # Expose the X display over VNC (port 5901). Use -rfbauth (preferred) and avoid deprecated/removed flags.
  x11vnc -display :1 -rfbport 5901 -forever -shared -rfbauth ~/.vnc/passwd -noxdamage -repeat -bg -o /tmp/x11vnc.log
  echo $! > /tmp/x11vnc.pid

  # Serve noVNC on port 12000, proxying to the VNC server
  websockify --web /usr/share/novnc --heartbeat 30 12000 localhost:5901 > /tmp/novnc.log 2>&1 & echo $! > /tmp/novnc.pid
  # Optional: also expose on 12001
  # websockify --web /usr/share/novnc --heartbeat 30 12001 localhost:5901 > /tmp/novnc-12001.log 2>&1 & echo $! > /tmp/novnc-12001.pid

  # Build the extension (from the repo root)
  # npm ci   # or npm install
  # npm run compile

  # Launch VS Code on the X display with the extension in development mode
  code --user-data-dir=/tmp/vscode-profile \
       --extensions-dir=/tmp/vscode-extensions \
       --no-sandbox --disable-gpu \
       --extensionDevelopmentPath=/workspace/project/OpenHands-Tab \
       > /tmp/code.log 2>&1 & echo $! > /tmp/code.pid

  Notes:
  - Start order matters: Xvfb -> WM (fluxbox) -> x11vnc -> websockify -> code.
  - You can adjust resolution if needed (e.g., 1440x900x24).

3.1) Quick verification (optional but recommended)
  netstat -ltnp | egrep ':(12000|12001)\s'  # noVNC listeners
  curl -sI http://127.0.0.1:12000/vnc.html   # should be HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  tail -n +1 /tmp/{xvfb,fluxbox,x11vnc,novnc,code}.log | sed -n '1,120p'

4) Access the desktop with your browser
- IMPORTANT: Do NOT append :12000 or :12001 to the URL. The platform maps each provided host to its internal port.
- Use the provided hosts for this workspace, for example:
  https://work-1-<your-suffix>.prod-runtime.all-hands.dev/vnc.html?autoconnect=true   # maps to internal 12000
  https://work-2-<your-suffix>.prod-runtime.all-hands.dev/vnc.html?autoconnect=true   # maps to internal 12001

- Authenticate with the VNC password when prompted. You should see the Fluxbox desktop and a VS Code window. Interact using your mouse/keyboard.

5) Running and testing the extension
- Build: npm install (or npm ci), then npm run compile to produce dist/ files.
- Launch: We use --extensionDevelopmentPath to run the extension in dev mode.
- In VS Code: open the command palette (Ctrl+Shift+P) and run the extension commands (e.g., "OpenHands: Open Tab").
- If the extension relies on a serverUrl setting, configure it in VS Code Settings: openhands.serverUrl.

6) Screenshots and optional recording
- Screenshots via noVNC toolbar: use the Screenshot button to download a PNG of the current view.
- Programmatic screenshots from the X display:
  # Using xwd + ImageMagick to PNG
  xwd -display :1 -root | convert xwd:- /workspace/shot.png

  # Or using ImageMagick import
  import -display :1 -window root /workspace/shot.png

- Optional: record a video of the session (adjust resolution/framerate as needed):
  apt-get install -y ffmpeg
  ffmpeg -y -video_size 1280x800 -framerate 30 -f x11grab -i :1.0 /workspace/session.mp4

7) Stop the services cleanly
- Kill the background processes using their recorded PIDs:
  for f in /tmp/{code,x11vnc,novnc,novnc-12001,wm,xvfb}.pid; do [ -f "$f" ] && kill "$(cat "$f")" || true; done

Troubleshooting tips
- If the noVNC page loads but shows a blank screen, verify x11vnc is running on :1 and that websockify is proxying to localhost:5901.
- If VS Code does not appear, ensure Fluxbox (or a minimal window manager) is running and that code is launched with DISPLAY=:1.
- If fonts/UI look off, install additional fonts: apt-get install -y fonts-dejavu fonts-liberation
- If the browser URL doesn’t load, remove any explicit :12000 or :12001 from the URL and use the provided host directly with /vnc.html.

Acceptance checklist
- Able to reach noVNC in the browser and see a desktop using the provided hosts (work-1/work-2 mapping).
- VS Code window is visible and interactive; extension runs in dev mode.
- At least one screenshot captured and saved to a known path (or downloaded via the toolbar).
- VNC access is password-protected.
